AIM:

To develop a basic Spring MVC application using annotation-based configuration. Create a controller to accept user requests and display employee details using the MVC flow without XML configuration.

PROCEDURE:

Create a Dynamic Web Project in Eclipse.

Add Spring MVC libraries to the project.

Create a Java package (for example: com.spring.mvc).

Create a class Employee with the fields:

Employee ID
Employee Name
Department

Create a Controller class using @Controller annotation.

Use @RequestMapping to accept user requests.

Use Model object to send employee data from controller to the view.

Create a configuration class using @Configuration, @EnableWebMvc, and @ComponentScan (no XML configuration).

Create a JSP page to display employee details.

Run the application using Apache Tomcat Server.

Test the application by opening the URL in the browser and verify that employee details are displayed using MVC flow.

CODE:
Employee.java
package com.spring.mvc;

public class Employee {

    private int empId;
    private String empName;
    private String department;

    public Employee(int empId, String empName, String department) {
        this.empId = empId;
        this.empName = empName;
        this.department = department;
    }

    public int getEmpId() {
        return empId;
    }

    public String getEmpName() {
        return empName;
    }

    public String getDepartment() {
        return department;
    }
}
EmployeeController.java
package com.spring.mvc;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Controller;
import org.springframework.ui.Model;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;

@Controller
public class EmployeeController {

    @RequestMapping("/employee")
    public String showEmployee(Model model) {

        Employee emp = new Employee(101, "Arun", "IT");

        model.addAttribute("emp", emp);

        return "employee";
    }
}
WebConfig.java (Configuration class – No XML)
package com.spring.mvc;

import org.springframework.context.annotation.ComponentScan;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.web.servlet.config.annotation.EnableWebMvc;

@Configuration
@EnableWebMvc
@ComponentScan(basePackages = "com.spring.mvc")
public class WebConfig {
}
DispatcherServlet Configuration (Initializer Class)
package com.spring.mvc;

import org.springframework.web.servlet.support.AbstractAnnotationConfigDispatcherServletInitializer;

public class AppInitializer 
        extends AbstractAnnotationConfigDispatcherServletInitializer {

    @Override
    protected Class<?>[] getRootConfigClasses() {
        return null;
    }

    @Override
    protected Class<?>[] getServletConfigClasses() {
        return new Class[] { WebConfig.class };
    }

    @Override
    protected String[] getServletMappings() {
        return new String[] { "/" };
    }
}
employee.jsp (View Page)

Create this file inside: WebContent/WEB-INF/views/employee.jsp

<%@ page contentType="text/html;charset=UTF-8" %>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Employee Details</title>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Employee Details</h2>

Employee ID: ${emp.empId} <br>
Employee Name: ${emp.empName} <br>
Department: ${emp.department}

</body>
</html>
RESULT:

Thus, a basic Spring MVC application was successfully developed using annotation-based configuration without XML.
The controller successfully accepted user requests using @RequestMapping, employee data was passed using the Model object, and the details were displayed in the JSP view using the MVC architecture.
